<subSubSection id="FDC3E2BC675BC98F1BC040216E7B911E" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="2E023314C0BD1608869C7359F98749A1" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">
<taxonomicName id="B9B4C16D1F1AAA12825B9CA0CECB82DF" family="Braconidae" genus="Protorhyssalinae" higherTaxonomySource="treatment-meta" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Protorhyssalinae">Protorhyssalinae</taxonomicName>
Basibuyuk, Quicke, &amp; van Achterberg, 1999: 211. Type genus: 
<taxonomicName id="AE61E24428B80834F13A7884C5F5CE4C" authorityName="Basibuyuk, Quickean Achterberg, Fitton &amp; Quicke" authorityYear="1999" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Protorhyssalus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Protorhyssalus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Protorhyssalus</taxonomicName>
Basibuyuk &amp; Quicke in 
<bibRefCitation id="87768637642942279EAC5353CF6AE7F4" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1046/j.1463-6409.1999.00006.x" author="Basibuyuk, HH" journalOrPublisher="Zoologica Scripta" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" pagination="211 - 214" refId="B4" refString="Basibuyuk, HH, Rasnitsyn, AP, van Achterberg, K, Fitton, MG, Quicke, DLJ, 1999. A new, putatively primitive Cretaceous fossil braconid subfamily from New Jersey amber (Hymenoptera, Braconidae). Zoologica Scripta 28 (1-2): 211 - 214, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1046/j.1463-6409.1999.00006.x" title="A new, putatively primitive Cretaceous fossil braconid subfamily from New Jersey amber (Hymenoptera, Braconidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1046/j.1463-6409.1999.00006.x" volume="28" year="1999">Basibuyuk et al. (1999)</bibRefCitation>
, by original designation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="22A0AB25FC358E6A3390E16F7D5CFE9F" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" type="comments">
<paragraph id="25751DA839497E2EBA19AB04374D768B" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B3E81A9A1FAC90ACA26D398287312148" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">
Herein we restore the traditional concept of † 
<taxonomicName id="00C336CD78F5CC05063EB6A19F445663" family="Braconidae" genus="Protorhyssalinae" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Protorhyssalinae">Protorhyssalinae</taxonomicName>
as recognized by 
<bibRefCitation id="D748E40A073424BC21594B430BDE563D" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1046/j.1463-6409.1999.00006.x" author="Basibuyuk, HH" journalOrPublisher="Zoologica Scripta" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" pagination="211 - 214" refId="B4" refString="Basibuyuk, HH, Rasnitsyn, AP, van Achterberg, K, Fitton, MG, Quicke, DLJ, 1999. A new, putatively primitive Cretaceous fossil braconid subfamily from New Jersey amber (Hymenoptera, Braconidae). Zoologica Scripta 28 (1-2): 211 - 214, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1046/j.1463-6409.1999.00006.x" title="A new, putatively primitive Cretaceous fossil braconid subfamily from New Jersey amber (Hymenoptera, Braconidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1046/j.1463-6409.1999.00006.x" volume="28" year="1999">Basibuyuk et al. (1999)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="F60095D83E63D6C4DFDF61E4919B992E" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1146/annurev-ento-011118-111856" author="Chen, XX" journalOrPublisher="Annual Review of Entomology" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" pagination="335 - 358" refId="B8" refString="Chen, XX, van Achterberg, C, 2019. Systematics, phylogeny, and evolution of braconid wasps: 30 years of progress. Annual Review of Entomology 64 (1): 335 - 358, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1146/annurev-ento-011118-111856" title="Systematics, phylogeny, and evolution of braconid wasps: 30 years of progress." url="https://doi.org/10.1146/annurev-ento-011118-111856" volume="64" year="2019">Chen and van Achterberg (2019)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="75EBD9AC12F6F824F6F6696BA92E911E" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.pgeola.2021.04.003" author="Belokobylskij, SA" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Geologists' Association" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" pagination="426 - 437" refId="B6" refString="Belokobylskij, SA, Jouault, C, 2021. Two new striking braconid genera (Hymenoptera: Braconidae) from the mid-Cretaceous Burmese amber. Proceedings of the Geologists' Association 132 (4): 426 - 437, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.pgeola.2021.04.003" title="Two new striking braconid genera (Hymenoptera: Braconidae) from the mid-Cretaceous Burmese amber." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.pgeola.2021.04.003" volume="132" year="2021">Belokobylskij and Jouault (2021)</bibRefCitation>
proposed a classification in which virtually all Cretaceous braconids are thrown into a paraphyletic group, rendering † 
<taxonomicName id="E69BBA7DBB84CB75FE0DBD6B0D9B45E7" family="Braconidae" genus="Protorhyssalinae" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Protorhyssalinae">Protorhyssalinae</taxonomicName>
a meaningless grade. Admittedly, restoring † 
<taxonomicName id="9CDD13EE3ADD1EB9E8152931FCA91F2F" family="Braconidae" genus="Protorhyssalinae" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Protorhyssalinae">Protorhyssalinae</taxonomicName>
still leaves the group paraphyletic but at least removes the more obviously derived groups and thereby narrows the challenge as to the affinities of the remaining genera. Nonetheless, while 
<bibRefCitation id="EF010D78271B51500D3C13211CD9209B" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.pgeola.2021.04.003" author="Belokobylskij, SA" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Geologists' Association" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" pagination="426 - 437" refId="B6" refString="Belokobylskij, SA, Jouault, C, 2021. Two new striking braconid genera (Hymenoptera: Braconidae) from the mid-Cretaceous Burmese amber. Proceedings of the Geologists' Association 132 (4): 426 - 437, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.pgeola.2021.04.003" title="Two new striking braconid genera (Hymenoptera: Braconidae) from the mid-Cretaceous Burmese amber." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.pgeola.2021.04.003" volume="132" year="2021">Belokobylskij and Jouault (2021)</bibRefCitation>
advocated for such a paraphyletic assemblage, they used plesiomorphic features along with autapomorphies to establish the subfamily † 
<taxonomicName id="BEE6D2576966720AAF15BE40772FD771" authorityName="Belokobylskij &amp; Jouault" authorityYear="2021" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Megalyrhyssalinae">Megalyrhyssalinae</taxonomicName>
. Unfortunately, † 
<taxonomicName id="BF5ABF16A18B4499823237F7967A3B1C" authorityName="Belokobylskij &amp; Jouault" authorityYear="2021" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Megalyrhyssalinae">Megalyrhyssalinae</taxonomicName>
is poorly justified and could be merely an autapomorphic form of the same protorhyssaline grade. By their own reasoning, they should have either not established such a subfamily or further divided † 
<taxonomicName id="5770A9FC6FA5E3EB519E7869A91CCC25" family="Braconidae" genus="Protorhyssalinae" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Protorhyssalinae">Protorhyssalinae</taxonomicName>
to resolve the paraphyly. Under their conception of † 
<taxonomicName id="E3DE9FC92559252141C5F3DC75604F8F" family="Braconidae" genus="Protorhyssalinae" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Protorhyssalinae">Protorhyssalinae</taxonomicName>
, † 
<taxonomicName id="5B876A6D4787D53091A85C210BD59EB0" authorityName="Belokobylskij &amp; Jouault" authorityYear="2021" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Megalyrhyssalinae">Megalyrhyssalinae</taxonomicName>
would be a junior synonym. For now, we recognize the following subfamilies: † 
<taxonomicName id="09BD7BB9D85D696CFA7598F7665C25E8" family="Braconidae" genus="Protorhyssalinae" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Protorhyssalinae">Protorhyssalinae</taxonomicName>
, † 
<taxonomicName id="25EA622C9936C17DF6DE0EC28DCAD6E5" authorityName="Engel &amp; Huang" authorityYear="2018" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Seneciobraconinae">Seneciobraconinae</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="CB31EBA5B8C3D1482D4D8F8565EDDEB1" authorityName="Engel &amp; Huang" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Seneciobracon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Seneciobracon" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8D9CC25C52AB277D4CCF232C73498540" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Seneciobracon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and † 
<taxonomicName id="03086BAE90FA22F7B66D7652F3A0832E" authorityName="Belokobylskij &amp; Jouault" authorityYear="2021" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Megalyrhyssalinae">Megalyrhyssalinae</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="13782A88306BDC24297BB144B0121C17" authorityName="Belokobylskij &amp; Jouault" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Megalyrhyssalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megalyrhyssalus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="911807C182079AA0BD4AA5F40EDEBA7F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Megalyrhyssalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), noting that the last may not be sufficiently justified but may well be worth considering once the full phylogeny of the genera comprising these groups is elucidated. Until such time it seems that further alterations of the subfamilial system in the absence of a cladistic framework would be unwarranted.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6B52B063EDA954048028F9FD7612BA9F" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" type="included genera and species">
<paragraph id="2A45233CBE99A5C2C69BB3B0C20137D8" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Included genera and species.</paragraph>
